Chapter 4: Hydraulic Pumps and Actuators

Chapter 4: Hydraulic Pumps and Actuators

Hydraulic pumps and actuators are identical in working principle and very similar in construction. Under certain conditions, you could even use some designs of pumps as motors and vice versa.

Dynamic pumps like aquarium circulation pumps or flood mitigation pumps work by imparting kinetic energy to the fluid. Positive displacement pumps, also known as static pumps, function by moving small volumes of liquid from the inlet to the outlet. This displacement motion can be rotational or reciprocating.

Since the action of the static pump is independent of system conditions downstream, the maximum pressure a positive displacement pump can generate depends on which component in the entire system fails first.

4.1 Hydraulic Pumps

Positive displacement pumps move liquid by reciprocating or rotary motion. The simplest kind is a single reciprocating piston pump illustrated in Figure 1.

Figure 1

Rotary pumps are the most commonly used in hydraulic systems. There are 3 general categories:

  1. Gear pumps
  2. Vane pumps
  3. Piston pumps

We can further differentiate them into different applications and functions:

  1. Gear pump
    • external
    • internal
    • gerotor
    • lobe
  2. Vane pump
    • fixed displacement
    • variable displacement
    • balanced
    • unbalanced
  3. Piston pump
    1. axial
      • bent-axis
      • swash plate
    2. radial

For the rest of this course, we will only deal with rotary pumps.

4.1.2 Gear pumps

The volumetric displacement of a gear pump is found by calculating the volume of the pump housing minus the volume of the gear hub. Half of the volume is taken up by gear teeth, but since there are 2 gears, we can treat it as one volume in calculation. The outer (D_{outer}DouterD_{outer}Douter​) and inner (D_{outer}DouterD_{outer}Douter​) diameter of the gear is used together with the width (LLLL) of the gear to give us the formula:

V_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_{outer}^2-D_{inner}^2)L
VD=π4(Douter2−Dinner2)LV_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_{outer}^2-D_{inner}^2)L VD​=4π​(Douter2​−Dinner2​)L

Example 4.2

A gear pump has a 75-mm outside diameter, a 50-mm inside diameter, and a 25-mm width. Find the volumetric displacement and flow rate at 1500 rpm.

4.1.3 Vane pumps

Vane pumps consist of a cam ring containing a slotted hub with vanes sitting inside. As the hub, or rotor, spins, springs and centrifugal force pushes the vanes against the housing, creating a sealed chamber. The hub is offset from the housing, creating eccentric circles. This offset creates chambers that expand and contract, creating suction and discharge.

In some designs of vane motor, the eccentricity can be adjusted, changing the difference between the largest and smallest chambers. This creates a variable displacement vane pump.

The eccentricity, eeee, is given as:

e=\frac{D_C-D_R}{2}
e=DC−DR2e=\frac{D_C-D_R}{2}e=2DC​−DR​​

where D_CDCD_CDC​ is the cam diameter and D_RDRD_RDR​ is the rotor diameter.

Similarly to the gear pump, the volumetric displacement of the pump starts with:

V_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_C^2-D_R^2)L
VD=π4(DC2−DR2)LV_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_C^2-D_R^2)LVD​=4π​(DC2​−DR2​)L

expanding the brackets,

V_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_C+D_R)(D_C-D_R)L
VD=π4(DC+DR)(DC−DR)LV_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_C+D_R)(D_C-D_R)LVD​=4π​(DC​+DR​)(DC​−DR​)L

substituting eeee, we obtain:

V_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_C+D_R)2eL
VD=π4(DC+DR)2eLV_D=\frac{\pi}{4}(D_C+D_R)2eLVD​=4π​(DC​+DR​)2eL

Example 4.3

A vane pump has a rotor diameter of 50 mm, a cam ring diameter of 75 mm, and a vane width of 50 mm. If the eccentricity is 8 mm, determine the volumetric displacement and flow rate in gpm at 800 rpm.

4.1.4 Piston Pumps

Piston pumps consist of a cylinder block containing multiple pistons arranged in a circular pattern. As the pump operates, a swash plate or cam mechanism drives the pistons in and out of their cylinders. This reciprocating motion creates alternating suction and discharge as the pistons draw in and expel fluid.

In some designs, the angle of the swash plate can be adjusted, changing the stroke length of the pistons. This variation controls the displacement, creating a variable displacement piston pump. Other designs, such as bent-axis pumps, have a set angle and thus a set volumetric displacement.

The volumetric displacement of a piston pump is thus the number of pistons mutiplied by the displacement volume per piston. The stroke of the piston, s, is offset at an angle, \thetaθ\thetaθ. As the pistons are set about a piston circle, the piston circle diameter (i.e. the circle the pistons are arranged around), D and the offset angle determine the effective stroke length of the piston.

By trigonometric analysis,
tan(\theta) = s/Dtan(θ)=s/Dtan(\theta) = s/Dtan(θ)=s/D
and
s = D \times tan(\theta)s=D×tan(θ)s = D \times tan(\theta)s=D×tan(θ)

Using this relation, we end up with the following equation for volumetric displacement:

V_D=YADtan(\theta)
VD=YADtan(θ)V_D=YADtan(\theta)VD​=YADtan(θ)

where Y is the number of pistons, and A is the piston area.

Example 4.4

Find the flow rate in units of L/s that an axial piston pump delivers at 1000 rpm. The pump has nine 15-mm-diameter pistons arranged on a 125-mm-diameter piston circle. The offset angle is set at 10°.

4.1.5 Efficiency

There is bound to be leakage between the gear and the pump housing as there needs to be clearance to allow for movement. The pump performance after accounting for leakage is called volumetric efficiency and is given by the formula:

\eta_v=\frac{Q_A}{Q_T}
ηv=QAQT\eta_v=\frac{Q_A}{Q_T}ηv​=QT​QA​​

Q_AQAQ_AQA​ is actual flowrate which is determined by testing, and Q_TQTQ_TQT​ is theoretical flowrate which is calculated in 4.1.1.

As components in the hydraulic system push, pull, and contact each other, friction causes energy loss. Fluid turbulence also contributes to energy loss. The output power accounting for these losses is called mechanical efficiency and is given by the formula:

\eta_m=\frac{PQ_T}{T_AN}
ηm=PQTTAN\eta_m=\frac{PQ_T}{T_AN}ηm​=TA​NPQT​​

where T_ATAT_ATA​ is the torque delivered to the pump, and N is the pump speed in rad/srad/srad/srad/s. This frames mechanical efficiency as pump output power divided by power delivered to the pump.

Another method to describe mechanical efficiency is to divide the torque theoretically required to drive the pump with the torque actually being drawn, shown as:

\eta_m=\frac{T_T}{T_A}
ηm=TTTA\eta_m=\frac{T_T}{T_A}ηm​=TA​TT​​

By putting both efficiencies, together, we can obtain the overall efficiency, or the power delivered by the pump divided by the power delivered to the pump

\eta_o=\eta_v \times \eta_m=\frac{Q_A}{Q_T} \times \frac{PQ_T}{T_AN}= \frac{PQ_A}{T_AN}
ηo=ηv×ηm=QAQT×PQTTAN=PQATAN\eta_o=\eta_v \times \eta_m=\frac{Q_A}{Q_T} \times \frac{PQ_T}{T_AN}= \frac{PQ_A}{T_AN}ηo​=ηv​×ηm​=QT​QA​​×TA​NPQT​​=TA​NPQA​​

4.2 Hydraulic Actuators

Hydraulic actuators fall into two general categories; linear and rotary. Cylinders provide linear motion, and motors provide rotary motion.

4.2.1 Hydraulic Cylinders

Cylinder construction can range from simple welded pieces to complex assemblies. All cylinders will have some form of piston to transmit force, a barrel to hold the piston, ports to allow fluid to flow, and seals to stop fluid from leaking.

The following link gives an overview of cylinders and cylinder construction.
https://www.lunchboxsessions.com/materials/hydraulic-actuators/anatomy-of-a-cylinder-lesson

The load the cylinder experience depends on the orientation of the weight being effected.

Vertical direction: The cylinder load is the weight of the object.

Horizontal direction: The cylinder load depends on the coefficient of friction between the object and the surface.

Neither vertical or horizontal: The cylinder load is the component of the object’s weight acting along the axis of the cylinder, plus a frictional force along the inclined surface

4.2.1.1 Loading Through Mechanical Linkage

In many applications, the load force that a hydraulic cylinder must overcome does not act along the axis of the hydraulic cylinder but along a mechanical linkage which can categorised as first (a), second (b), and third-class (c) levers, as shown below.

To determine the cylinder force Fcyl required to drive a load force Fload,we
equate moments about the fixed hinge. This gives us the formulas below:

First-class:

	F_{cyl}=\frac{L_2}{L_1cos \phi}F_{load}
Fcyl=L2L1cosϕFload F_{cyl}=\frac{L_2}{L_1cos \phi}F_{load}Fcyl​=L1​cosϕL2​​Fload​

Second-class:

	F_{cyl}=\frac{L_2}{(L_1+L_2)cos \phi}F_{load}
Fcyl=L2(L1+L2)cosϕFload F_{cyl}=\frac{L_2}{(L_1+L_2)cos \phi}F_{load}Fcyl​=(L1​+L2​)cosϕL2​​Fload​

Third-class:

	F_{cyl}=\frac{L_1+L_2}{L_2\ cos \phi}F_{load}
Fcyl=L1+L2L2 cosϕFload F_{cyl}=\frac{L_1+L_2}{L_2\ cos \phi}F_{load}Fcyl​=L2​ cosϕL1​+L2​​Fload​

4.2.1.3 Types of cylinder mounting

  1. Clevis mount: A fork-shaped connection with a pin for easy attachment to a fixed point.
  2. Flange mount
    1. Front flange: Attached to the cylinder's front with bolts for secure mounting.
    2. Rear flange: Mounted at the rear, often with bolts to connect to a machine.
  3. Trunnion mount: A cylindrical pin connection allowing rotation around a central axis.
  4. Foot mount: Flat, bolted base providing stable mounting for the cylinder.

Double-acting cylinders sometimes contain cylinder cushions at the ends of the cylinder to slow the piston down near the ends of the stroke.This prevents excessive impact when the piston is stopped by the end caps.

4.2.2 Hydraulic Motors

Hydraulic motors extract energy from a fluid and convert it to mechanical energy to perform useful work. There are two types:

  1. Limited rotation or rotary actuator or oscillating motor
  2. Continuous rotation type or hydraulic motor

Limited rotation motor can rotate clockwise and counter-clockwise but through less than one complete revolution.

Continuous rotation motor can rotate continuously at a speed that is determined by the motor’s input flow rate.

4.2.2.1 Limited Rotation Motor

Limited rotation motors consist of a chamber and a vane connected to the output shaft. The fluid entering the chamber at pressure produces a force against the surface area of the vane, which is transmitted to the shaft as a torque.

The area of the vane can be formulated as:
A_{vane}=(r_v-r_s)LAvane=(rv−rs)LA_{vane}=(r_v-r_s)LAvane​=(rv​−rs​)L

where r_vrvr_vrv​ is the outer radius of the vane, r_srsr_srs​ is the outer radius of the shaft, and LLLL is the width of the vane.

The force on the vane can then be found using:

F=PA_{vane}=P(r_v-r_s)L
F=PAvane=P(rv−rs)LF=PA_{vane}=P(r_v-r_s)LF=PAvane​=P(rv​−rs​)L

The torque generated by the motor is thus the force at the vane multiplied by the mean radius of the vane:

T=P(r_v-r_s)L \times \frac{r_v-r_s}{2}
T=P(rv−rs)L×rv−rs2T=P(r_v-r_s)L \times \frac{r_v-r_s}{2}T=P(rv​−rs​)L×2rv​−rs​​

or

T=\frac{PL}{2}(r_v^2-r_s^2)
T=PL2(rv2−rs2)T=\frac{PL}{2}(r_v^2-r_s^2)T=2PL​(rv2​−rs2​)

Example 4.12

A single-vane limited rotation motor has a shaft outer radius of 15 mm, vane outer radius of 40 mm, and vane length of 25 mm. What is the pressure required to produce 150 Nm of torque?

4.2.2.2 Continuous gear motor

Torque in gear motors is developed by hydraulic pressure acting on teeth surfaces. The direction of rotation can be reversed by changing the direction of the flow of liquid. This pressure differential causes a large side loading on the shaft and bearings.

The main advantage of gear motors is simple construction and maintenance, low cost, and robustness. However, they have lower efficiency than other designs with about 70-75% and are always fixed displacement.

4.2.2.3 Continuous vane motor

Pressure acting on the vanes causes a torque which spins the shaft. Some designs place 2 inlets and 2 outlets opposite each other, creating a balanced load. They are relatively efficient with 75-85% efficiency and suitable for fluids with low viscosity. Due to the eccentricity of the rotor and hub, vane motors can be designed to provide variable displacement. However, they are not suitable for high pressure applications.

4.2.2.4 Continuous piston motor

Pressure acting on the ends of the piston create reciprocation inside the cylinder block. This causes the cylinder block to rotate with a torque that is proportional to the area of the piston. Piston motors give high speed and displacement control and are more efficient at 85-95% efficiency. They can also handle high pressure and high torque applications. However, the large number of components make it expensive and complicated to maintain. It is also sensitive to contamination.

4.2.2.3 Motor performance and efficiency

Similarly to rotary pumps, the performance of a motor can be described with the formulas for flow rate, torque, and power.

Q_T(m^3/s)=V_D \times N
QT(m3/s)=VD×NQ_T(m^3/s)=V_D \times NQT​(m3/s)=VD​×N

where NNNN is in revolutions per second.

T_T(Nm)=\frac{V_D \times P}{2 \pi}
TT(Nm)=VD×P2πT_T(Nm)=\frac{V_D \times P}{2 \pi}TT​(Nm)=2πVD​×P​

and

Power=T_T \times N
Power=TT×NPower=T_T \times NPower=TT​×N

where NNNN is in radians per second.

Unlike rotary pumps which consume more torque than expected to produce less flow than expected, rotary motors consume more flow than expected to produce less torque than expected. This is shown in the formulas for efficiency:

\eta_v=\frac{Q_T}{Q_A}

ηo=ηv×ηm=TA×NP×QA\eta_o=\eta_v \times \eta_m=\frac{T_A \times N}{P \times Q_A}ηo​=ηv​×ηm​=P×QA​TA​×N​

where NNNN is in radians per second
